# ============================================================================
# greenroom — environment variable template
# ============================================================================
#
# What is this file?
#   This is a TEMPLATE. It lives in git and shows what variables the app needs.
#   It has placeholder values like `xxxxxxxx`, NOT real ones.
#
# How do I use it?
#   1. Copy this file to a file named `.env` in the same folder:
#        cp .env.example .env
#   2. Open `.env` in your editor.
#   3. Replace each placeholder value with a real value from the instructions
#      below. Keep the variable NAMES exactly the same; only change what's
#      AFTER the `=` sign.
#
# Will my real .env get pushed to GitHub?
#   No. `.env` is listed in `.gitignore`, which tells git to ignore it.
#   Confirm this by running:
#     git check-ignore -v .env
#   If it prints a `.gitignore` line, you're safe.
#
# What prefix do variables use? Why "EXPO_PUBLIC_"?
#   Expo (the framework we use) only includes env vars in the built app if
#   they start with `EXPO_PUBLIC_`. Anything without that prefix is only
#   visible to Node during local scripts — it will NOT ship with the app.
#   All four variables below MUST keep that prefix or the app won't find them.
#
# Are any of these values "secret"? Can I share them?
#   The four values below are SAFE to have on the device and (in a pinch) to
#   share — they're designed to be visible to the client app. Supabase
#   enforces security via RLS (Row-Level Security) on the server side, so
#   having the publishable key doesn't let anyone read your data.
#
#   HOWEVER: there's one TRULY secret thing mentioned below — the Google Web
#   **client SECRET** (not client ID). That one is sensitive. It only ever
#   lives in the Supabase dashboard, never in this file or in git.
#
# After editing `.env`, restart the dev server with:
#     npx expo start -c
#   The `-c` clears Expo's cache. Env vars are baked in at startup, so if you
#   change `.env`, you must restart with `-c` for changes to take effect.
#
# ============================================================================


# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1) Supabase — the cloud service that stores data and handles logins
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Where to get these two values:
#   1. Go to https://supabase.com and log in.
#   2. Click the greenroom project. (If none exists, ask Jesse to create one
#      and add you as a collaborator.)
#   3. In the left sidebar click "Project Settings" (gear icon), then "API".
#   4. Copy the "Project URL" — it looks like:
#        https://abcdefghijklmnop.supabase.co
#      Paste it after `EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=` below.
#   5. Copy the "anon public" key — it's a long string starting with
#      `sb_publishable_`. Paste it after `EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=`.
#      (If you see an older "anon" key starting with `eyJ...` — that's the
#      legacy JWT-style key; we use the new publishable format. Ask Jesse if
#      only the legacy one exists.)

EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project.supabase.co
EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=sb_publishable_xxxxxxxx


# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2) Google OAuth — lets users sign in with their Google account
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# OAuth (Open Authorization) is the standard way apps let users log in via
# a third party ("Sign in with Google"). Google needs to know:
#   - Which app is asking? (identified by a "Client ID")
#   - Where should the login result go back to? (a "redirect URI")
#
# We need TWO Google clients — an iOS one (for the phone) and a Web one
# (which Supabase uses to verify the login on its server). Different jobs,
# different client IDs.
#
# Where to set this up:
#   1. Go to https://console.cloud.google.com and log in.
#   2. Create a project called "greenroom" (or use an existing one).
#   3. In the search bar at the top, search for "OAuth consent screen" and
#      open it.
#        - User type: External.
#        - App name: greenroom
#        - User support email: your email
#        - Developer contact: your email
#        - Leave scopes blank for now. Save.
#        - Add yourself as a "Test user" so you're allowed to log in during
#          development.
#   4. Search for "Credentials" in the search bar and open it.
#
# ---- Create the iOS client ----
#   5. Click "+ Create credentials" → "OAuth client ID".
#   6. Application type: **iOS**.
#   7. Name: greenroom iOS
#   8. Bundle ID: **com.codeflixacademy.greenroom**
#      (This must match `ios.bundleIdentifier` in `app.json`. If we ever
#      change that, we have to update this too.)
#   9. Click "Create".
#  10. Copy the "Client ID" (ends with `.apps.googleusercontent.com`).
#      Paste it after `EXPO_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_IOS_CLIENT_ID=` below.
#      (The iOS client doesn't need a "secret" — iOS apps can't keep
#      secrets, so Google doesn't issue one. That's normal.)

EXPO_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_IOS_CLIENT_ID=xxxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx.apps.googleusercontent.com

# ---- Create the Web client ----
#  11. Back on Credentials, click "+ Create credentials" → "OAuth client ID"
#      again.
#  12. Application type: **Web application**.
#  13. Name: greenroom Web (used by Supabase)
#  14. Authorized redirect URIs: click "+ Add URI" and add BOTH of these:
#        a) https://<YOUR_SUPABASE_PROJECT_REF>.supabase.co/auth/v1/callback
#           (Replace `<YOUR_SUPABASE_PROJECT_REF>` with the subdomain from
#            your Supabase URL. e.g. if your URL is
#            https://abcdefghijklmnop.supabase.co, the redirect is
#            https://abcdefghijklmnop.supabase.co/auth/v1/callback)
#        b) https://auth.expo.io/@YOUR_EXPO_USERNAME/greenroom
#           (Replace `YOUR_EXPO_USERNAME` with your Expo account username.
#            Sign up at https://expo.dev if you don't have one yet, then
#            run `npx expo login` in the terminal to log in.)
#  15. Click "Create". A pop-up shows:
#        - Client ID (long string) — copy it; paste after
#          `EXPO_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_WEB_CLIENT_ID=` below.
#        - Client secret (shorter string) — copy it; you'll paste it into
#          the Supabase dashboard in the NEXT section, NOT into this file.

EXPO_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_WEB_CLIENT_ID=xxxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx.apps.googleusercontent.com


# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 3) Supabase dashboard — tell Supabase to accept Google logins
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# This part is NOT about `.env`. It's about clicking through the Supabase
# dashboard. Do this AFTER finishing the Google steps above.
#
#   1. Back in Supabase (https://supabase.com → your project).
#   2. Left sidebar → "Authentication" → "Providers".
#   3. Find "Google" in the list, click it, toggle "Enable".
#   4. Paste the **Web client ID** (the one you saved as
#      EXPO_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_WEB_CLIENT_ID) into the "Client ID" field.
#   5. Paste the **Web client SECRET** (the one I warned you not to put in
#      `.env`) into the "Client Secret" field.
#   6. Leave the other fields at their defaults.
#   7. Click "Save".
#
# That's it. Supabase will now accept Google ID tokens whose `aud` field
# matches your Web client ID.


# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 4) Apple Sign In — not set up yet (deferred until Phase N8)
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# The app has an "Sign in with Apple" button but we are NOT testing it yet.
# It needs:
#   - An Apple Developer Program membership ($99/year)
#   - A Sign In with Apple service ID configured against
#     bundle ID `com.codeflixacademy.greenroom`
#   - Key ID, team ID, and private key pasted into Supabase dashboard
#     under Authentication → Providers → Apple
#
# During development (Phases N1 through N7), use Google Sign In only.
# We'll circle back to Apple in Phase N8 when we set up TestFlight.


# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Checklist — have you filled in all four?
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
#   [ ] EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL
#   [ ] EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY
#   [ ] EXPO_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_IOS_CLIENT_ID
#   [ ] EXPO_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_WEB_CLIENT_ID
#
# And the two dashboard-side items (not in this file):
#
#   [ ] Google Web **client secret** pasted into Supabase → Auth → Providers
#       → Google (NOT into this file)
#   [ ] Both Google redirect URIs added to the Web client in Google Cloud:
#         - https://<supabase-ref>.supabase.co/auth/v1/callback
#         - https://auth.expo.io/@<your-expo-username>/greenroom
#
# Now restart the dev server:
#   npx expo start -c
